In C++, regex (regular expressions) are used for pattern matching in strings. 
They are part of the <regex> library introduced in C++11.

#include <regex>

Basic Components

| Component       | Meaning                     |
| --------------- | --------------------------- |
| `regex`         | Defines a pattern           |
| `regex_match`   | Matches entire string       |
| `regex_search`  | Finds pattern inside string |
| `regex_replace` | Replaces matched pattern    |


regex pattern("...")

This creates a regex object (pattern) that defines the pattern to be matched.
In the example, `regex pattern("[^a-z0-9]")` defines a pattern that matches any character that is NOT a lowercase letter (a-z) or a digit (0-9).

regex_match()
This function checks if the entire string matches the regex pattern.
example: `regex_match(s, pattern)` returns true if the entire string `s` matches the pattern defined by `pattern`.

regex_search()
This function checks if any part of the string matches the regex pattern.
example: `regex_search(s, pattern)` returns true if any substring of `s` matches the pattern defined by `pattern`.

regex_replace()
This function replaces all occurrences of the regex pattern in the string with a specified replacement.
example: `regex_replace(s, pattern, replacement)` returns a new string with all matches of `pattern` replaced by `replacement`.

smatch match This is a type used to store the results of a regex search. It contains information about the matched substring, such as its position and length.

After regex_search, you can access:
- `match[0]`: The entire matched substring.
- `match[1]`, `match[2]`, etc.: Captured groups if the regex pattern contains parentheses for grouping.

Important Regex Symbols (MOST IMPORTANT)
| Symbol | Meaning                          |
| ------ | -------------------------------- |
| `.`    | Matches any single character      |
| `*`    | Matches zero or more occurrences  |
| `+`    | Matches one or more occurrences   |
| `?`    | Matches zero or one occurrence    |
| `^`    | Matches the start of the string   |
| `$`    | Matches the end of the string     |
| `[]`   | Matches any one of the characters inside the brackets |
| `()`   | Groups patterns together          |
Example: `regex pattern("[a-z]+")` matches one or more lowercase letters`.   
Example: `regex pattern("^[a-z0-9]+$")` matches a string that consists entirely of lowercase letters and digits.

| Syntax  | Meaning              |
| ------- | -------------------- |
| `a`     | exact character      |
| `.`     | any single character |
| `[abc]` | a or b or c          |
| `[a-z]` | lowercase letters    |
| `[A-Z]` | uppercase letters    |
| `[0-9]` | digits               |
